---
alwaysApply: true
---

Treat Custom Locations as optional, delayed, and fallible. The experience must function correctly before, during, and after location locking.

Core Requirement

Your system must support three states at all times:

Pre-lock (no location yet)
Locking (unstable / adjusting)
Locked (stable anchor available)

The app must remain usable in all three.

Execution Behavior
1. Never block on Custom Location readiness
Do NOT wait for a successful scan to allow interaction
Users must be able to:
drop pins
see pins
sync pins
even without a locked location
2. Always maintain a fallback coordinate system

Before Custom Location locks:

Use local/world space relative to device start
Store positions in this temporary space

After lock:

Convert or remap positions into location-relative space
3. Treat location lock as a correction, not a starting point

When a Custom Location becomes available:

Do NOT respawn everything abruptly
Smoothly reconcile positions:
lerp / ease into corrected positions
avoid visual “jumping”
4. Assume drift, relocalization, and failure

On Spectacles:

Tracking can shift
Location can lose lock
Users move fast / environments change

Your system must:

Re-anchor or adjust objects continuously
Avoid “hard snapping” unless necessary
Rebuild state if tracking resets
5. Store positions relative to the location, not absolute world

Once locked:

All persistent data must be:
location-relative (local space of LocationAsset)
NOT:
raw world coordinates

This ensures:

cross-session persistence
correct ghost pin placement later
6. Minimize dependence on precise surfaces

Do NOT rely on:

perfect plane detection
exact mesh alignment

Instead:

use approximate anchors + visual affordances (beacons, floating pins)

(This matches your design intent from Flâneur.)

7. Always degrade gracefully

If Custom Location fails:

Replace precise pins with:
radius-based markers
directional indicators
approximate beacons

The experience should feel intentional, not broken

Hard Prohibitions
Do NOT assume Custom Location will succeed
Do NOT tie core interactions exclusively to location lock
Do NOT store permanent data in raw world coordinates
Do NOT let objects disappear when tracking is lost
Guiding Principle

Custom Location is a refinement layer, not the foundation.

Your true foundation is:

relative spatial relationships
shared multiplayer state

Custom Locations only improve accuracy—they do not define the experience.
